<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="prep-9-18">
  <title>Resources for 9/18</title>

  <objectives>
    <introduction>
      <p>For the content of this class, you will be expected to be able to do the following:</p>
    </introduction>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          For an applied problem involving a linear function, use your understanding of linear functions to interpret the function and make predictions.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-application-linear">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Applying Linear Functions</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video on <em></em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="kaOGjmN3YwA" />

    <example>
      <title>Applying Linear Functions</title>
      <p>
        Jojo is now selling commemorative plates.  Jojo's marketing analyst says that if Jojo sells the plates for $5 each, they can sell 200 plates, and if Jojo sells the plates for $20 each, they can sell 110 plates.  Suppose that if Jojo sells the plates at $p per plate, the amount sold is <m>d(p)</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              What are <m>d(5)</m> and <m>d(20)</m>?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose that the function <m>d</m> is a linear function of <m>p</m>.  What is the slope of <m>d</m>?  Include the units.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              What does the number you found in #2 tell us about what will happen if Jojo increases the price of the plates?  Or decreases the price of the plates?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find a formula for <m>d(p)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              How many plates will Jojo sell if the price is $10?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="video-activity-quadratic-equations">
    <title>Video &amp; Activities for Quadratic Equations</title>
    <p>
      Below is a YouTube video reviewing solving <em>quadratic equations</em>. It is followed by a link to a set of activities that we will be working on in class. Please watch the video and do as many of the activities as you can before class.
    </p>

    <video youtube="86PzWJkckKI" />

    <example>
      <title>Quadratic Equations (Not on Quiz)</title>
      <p>
        The following problems are meant to be a review of solving quadratic equations.
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2+4x+3=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>x^2+2x-15=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>3x^2+7x+2=0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>4x^2-7x=2</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Suppose you are fencing in a rectangular region of area 100 square feet.  If the length is 21 feet longer than the width, find the dimensions of the fencing.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>2x^2+4x=13</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>3x^2+6x=-13</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              You stand on a ledge 10 ft above the ground and throw a ball up in the air.  The height of the ball at time <m>t</m> seconds is <m>h(t) = -16t^2+32t+10</m> feet. At what time does the ball hit the ground?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </example>
    <p>
      Feel free to post any questions you have on the <url href="">FigJam board</url> for the next class.
    </p>
  </subsection>

